# Ship workflow (musician-ai-studio)

When you finish a task that **changes tracked project files** (especially `www/`, `src/`, root `index.html` / `styles.css`, `api/`, or anything that affects the shipped web or native shell), do this **before ending the turn** unless the user explicitly says not to. **Do not wait for the user to say “commit / push / sync”** — they want this every time by default.

1. **`git status`** — confirm what changed.
2. **`npm run stamp:build`** — stamps a fresh, unique build id into the cache-busting asset URLs (`styles.css?v=…`, `src/app.js?v=…`) and the `APP_BUILD` marker, **and** mirrors everything into `www/` (it runs `sync-www` internally). Always run this when shipping web/native changes: the static `?v=` is what busts the WKWebView (native) and browser/CDN caches, so without a bump the device/web keep serving stale code (the recurring "I don't see my change" problem). The id also shows in the faint on-screen build marker, so you can confirm a device got the new build. If you only need to mirror without shipping (e.g. a sim preview mid-iteration), use `npm run sync:www` instead to avoid churning the version.
3. **`git add`** the relevant paths (including the stamped `index.html`, `src/app.js`, and their `www/` mirrors) and **`git commit -m "…"`** with a short, accurate message (full sentences, no fluff).
4. **`git push`** to the current branch’s upstream (usually `origin main`). That is the deploy step for the web app when the GitHub repo is connected to Vercel; do not wait for the user to ask.
5. **`npm run run:ios`** from the repo root — syncs `www` into the iOS shell (`sync:ios` inside the script), **builds** for the connected iPhone, **installs**, and **launches** the app (no Xcode debugger). Do **not** stop at `npx cap sync ios` alone unless `run:ios` fails (no device, signing error, etc.); report the failure and what succeeded up to that point.
6. If `run:ios` changes tracked files under `ios/`, commit and push those too in the same pass.

Skip only when there is **nothing to commit** (clean tree after sync) or the user asked to leave git alone. If push fails, fix or report and do not claim success. If build/launch fails after a successful push, say so clearly — web deploy may still be live.
